Of AIDS, eight key non-communicable diseases.
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as cardiovascular diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is conclusive evidence that smoking, a sedentary lifestyle, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of premature death from non-communicable diseases.
Despite a broad understanding of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It's within this context that NCD networks came together from 9 to 11 December at the second Global Alliance for NCDs Forum in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to regulate NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the AIDS fight movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress made.
While the fight is not over, AIDS activists know they can win this fight.
In their search for solutions to regulate NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the AIDS fight movement. People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress made. While the fight is not over, AIDS activists know they can win this fight. Similarly, a mobilization movement against NCDs can help reverse this epidemic.
Despite this, in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the NCD community as waiting for "an electric shock to its semi-comatose mind." He added, "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
While global attention focuses on preventing NCDs, those seeking to control avoidable diseases should draw inspiration from the ABCs of AIDS advocacy groups.
The first letter the NCD community should consider is "A," as activism.
Everyone over 40 surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-in" protests during scientific conferences worldwide.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even shutting down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
At the global level, activists have pressed governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
The NCD community should then adopt a bolder approach to budgets - the "B" of the AIDS movement's strategy.
Civil society organization and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires funding.
The AIDS movement has been clear about this from the outset and has pressed for resources to support its awareness-raising and accountability activities effectively.
"C" represents coalitions: the AIDS movements quickly understood that progress comes only with multiple supporters.
Activists have established connections between people living with HIV and those concerned with other issues, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Specialized coalitions and campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders to the public sector, combining their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS movement has also understood that a global response to the epidemic is crucial to spreading its support.
Thus, "D", the determining factor of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer contributed to equipping young people with knowledge and the power to make informed decisions about the timing and partner for protected sex.
Similarly, connections have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that have played a driving role in the AIDS crisis.
NCDs are not less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multi-sectoral approach to prevention.
Engagement - "E" - has been what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategic borrowings from the disability rights movement, which championed the rallying cry "Nothing about us without us," AIDS advocates demanded representation of existing bodies to address the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only UN agency with seats on its Board of Directors reserved for civil society representatives.
This standard has become so deeply ingrained in the AIDS movement that it would be almost unthinkable for an AIDS conference to take place without representation from the community.
The disease prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives and "F" - the framing of the question - is crucial for the AIDS community to gain the support of political leaders.
In particular, access to AIDS treatments has been presented as a matter of economic justice.
Formulating the story in this way leads to a significant reduction in the price of medications, to the point that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
A formulation equally crucial to the AIDS issue, a question highly relevant to the NCD movement, is that of accountability.
The AIDS community has worked hard to focus more on individual lifestyle choices, rather than holding the state accountable for healthcare provision and the elimination of legal discrimination.
In the AIDS debate, gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant factor.
HIV was initially considered a "gay disease" and gender identity was entrenched from the outset in the DNA of the AIDS movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it's enough to look at how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Gender, therefore, must become a hub of NCD prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" - human rights - is the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against workplace discrimination, in schools, and in healthcare centers.
Strategic litigation has ensured legal equality.
The AIDS movement has refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The NCD movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods for children.
We could continue the list of lessons learned from the fight against AIDS throughout the alphabet, but it seems fitting to close it on "H", given that human rights have provided the response to AIDS and should provide the response to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
It is the same for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask, "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS movement has clearly said that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet facing premature death due to preventable diseases, "those people" represent a significant number of us.
The NCD and AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The views expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
